    "summary": "On March 21, 1960, South African police opened fire on a crowd of approximately 7,000 Black South Africans who had gathered at the Sharpeville police station to protest the pass laws requiring Black Africans to carry identification documents at all times. The police fired without warning, killing 69 people and wounding 180, many shot in the back while fleeing. The massacre shocked the world and became a turning point in South Africa's history and in international attitudes toward the [[event:2684|apartheid]] system.\n\nThe Sharpeville Massacre led the government to declare a state of emergency and ban the African National Congress and Pan Africanist Congress, driving both organizations underground. The ANC's decision to adopt armed struggle followed directly from the conclusion that peaceful protest would be met with lethal force. Internationally, the massacre triggered the first serious calls for economic sanctions against South Africa at the United Nations. March 21 is now commemorated as Human Rights Day in South Africa. The date of the massacre was deliberately chosen for the signing of the post-apartheid constitution in 1996, symbolically connecting the new democratic order to the struggle against apartheid violence.",
